The Plantiff brings a Quare Impedit against Nicholson Passfield and Bishop of London, as Ordinary for the Church of C. and shews Sir T.M. was seized and presented Passfield, and let the Mannour to which the Advowson is appendant to the Plantiff. The Church became void by pas. resign. so it belonged to him to present, Bishop pleads as Ordinary, Passfield intitles by presentation as to Advowson in gross, and traverse append. Plantiff takes issue, Nicholson pleads under the King, and confesses the title of Sir T.M. and the Lease abovesaid, pleads over, Sir T.M. pro quadam. pec. summ. presented Passfield, and pleads 31. Eliz. cap. 6. It was urged that the plea was nought, and not shewing what summe of Money was given, is not good. But the Pourt, The plea is good: For the plea makes the traverse but argumentative, that he might not resigne;
and being alledged the Church is void, per mort. vel resignat. it ought to be confessed or traversed, and the issue ought to have been taken si vacavit per mortem vel &c. Dyer 376. Cooks Entrys 499. Says Case, H. 15. Jac. rot. 2091. Paschall •
Case; Simony alledged, and presentment of the King therefore, &c. Vacancy per mort. traversed. So M. 2. Car. Entrys, 485. 490: 511.
